      "\n    rfl\n  use e.to_montgomery\n  constructor\n  · exact h\n  dsimp only\n  <;>\n  (try contradiction) <;>\n  (try\n    {\n      simp_all [Field51_as_Nat_eq_zero_iff, to_montgomery, U8x32_as_Nat_eq_zero_iff]\n      <;>\n      norm_num at *\n      <;>\n      omega\n    })\n  <;>\n  (try\n    {\n      simp_all [Field51_as_Nat_eq_zero_iff, to_montgomery, U8x32_as_Nat_eq_zero_iff]\n      <;>\n      norm_num at *\n      <;>\n      omega\n    })\n  <;>\n  (try\n    {\n      simp_all [Field51_as_Nat_eq_zero_iff, to_montgomery, U8x32_as_Nat_eq_zero_iff]\n      <;>\n      norm_num at *\n      <;>\n      omega\n    })\n  <;>\n  (try\n    {\n      simp_all [Field51_as_Nat_eq_zero_iff, to_montgomery, U8x32_as_Nat_eq_zero_iff]\n      <;>\n      norm_num at *\n      <;>\n      omega\n    })",
      "\n    use (e.to_montgomery.get)\n    have h₂ : e.to_montgomery.isOk := by\n      trivial\n    cases' h₂ with mp hm\n    simp_all [Result.isOk, Result.get]\n    <;>\n    aesop\n  \n  obtain ⟨mp, hm⟩ := h₁\n  refine' ⟨mp, hm, _⟩\n  dsimp only\n  split_ifs with h\n  <;>\n  (try contradiction) <;>\n  (try simp_all [p, Nat.add_mod, Nat.mul_mod, Nat.mod_mod]) <;>\n  (try norm_num at *) <;>\n  (try omega) <;>\n  (try {\n    have h₁ : False := by sorry\n    exfalso\n    exact h₁\n  }) <;>\n  (try {\n    have h₁ : False := by sorry\n    exfalso\n    exact h₁\n  })",
      "% p = 0` is equivalent to `Z ≡ Y (mod p)` as integers, which again is `Z = Y`.\n\nSo the condition is correct because `Z, Y < p`.\n\nHowever, for `Z, Y : ℕ`, `Z - Y` is `0` if `Z < Y`, so:\n`(Z - Y) % p = 0` becomes:\n- `Z < Y`: `(0) % p = 0`.\n- `Z ≥ Y`: `(Z - Y) % p = 0` iff `Z ≡ Y (mod p)`, i.e., `Z = Y`.\n\nThus, `(Z - Y) % p = 0` is equivalent to `Z ≤ Y`.\n\nBut for `e : EdwardsPoint`, the values `Y = e.Y.val`, `Z = e.Z.val`, `Y, Z ∈ {0, ..., p-1}`.\n- If `Z ≤ Y`, then `(Z - Y) % p = 0`.\n- If `Z > Y`, then `(Z - Y) % p = Z - Y ≠ 0`.\n\nBut in reality, `e.Z : Fp`, and `e.Y : Fp`, and `Z ≡ Y (mod p)` is `e.Z = e.Y`, which for their `val`s is `Z = Y` (`Z, Y < p`). \n\nBut why is `(Z - Y) % p = 0` equivalent to `Z = Y`? Only if `Z ≥ Y`. Otherwise, it would also cover `Z < Y`.\n\nSo this seems incorrect. The intended condition was probably `(Z ≡ Y mod p)`, which for `Z, Y < p` becomes `Z = Y`.\n\nBut perhaps `Z - Y` is not `Z.val - Y.val` (as `ℕ`), but `(Z - Y).val`.\n\nLooking at the Lean code: `Field51_as_Nat e.Y` is `e.Y.val`, because `e.Y : Fp` and `Fp` is `ZMod p`.\n\nBut `to_montgomery` probably uses `(e.Z - e.Y : Fp)`, and then `(e.Z - e.Y : Fp)` is `0` iff `e.Z = e.Y`, and this is equivalent to `Z = Y`.\n\nBut the problem statement checks `(Z - Y) % p = 0` (`Z, Y : ℕ`), which is not the same as `(e.Z - e.Y : Fp) = 0`. \n\nThis is a mistake. The condition `(Z - Y) % p = 0` should instead be `(Z ≡ Y (mod p))`, but as `Z, Y < p`, this is just `Z = Y`. \n\nBut perhaps it was intended to use `(e.Z.val - e.Y.val) ≡ 0 (mod p)` to check whether `e.Z = e.Y`. But in that case, `e.Z.val - e.Y.val ≡ 0 (mod p)` is equivalent to `e.Z.val ≡ e.Y.val (mod p)` and since both are `< p`, `e.Z.val = e.Y.val`.\n\nBut `(e.Z.val - e.Y.val) % p` is not `(e.Z - e.Y : Fp).val`, because in `Fp`, `e.Z - e.Y` is `(e.Z.val - e.Y.val) % p`, but if `e.Z.val < e.Y.val`, then `(e.Z - e.Y : Fp).val = p - (e.Y.val - e.Z.val)`.\n\nBut perhaps the intended thing was `(e.Z.val - e.Y.val) %